## 🐛 Bug Report

Lib version: 4.3.0 

## Steps To Reproduce

When passing in an array of values to addRow, the values get added to the file in normal execution but does not get added to the file when creating it through Node's VM runInNewContext.

```javascript
const excelJS = require('exceljs');
const vm = require('vm');
(async () => {
    const workbook1 = new excelJS.Workbook();
    const sheet1 = workbook1.addWorksheet('Data');
    sheet1.addRow(['test', 'these', 'values']);
    sheet1.addRow(['and', 'also', 'these', 'values']);
    await workbook1.xlsx.writeFile('file1.xlsx');

    vm.runInNewContext(`
        (async () => {
            const workbook2 = new excelJS.Workbook();
            const sheet2 = workbook2.addWorksheet('Data');
            sheet2.addRow(['test', 'these', 'values']);
            sheet2.addRow(['and', 'also', 'these', 'values']);
            await workbook2.xlsx.writeFile('file2.xlsx');
        })();
    `, {excelJS: excelJS});
})();
```

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/30079507/147269253-7bbf8bef-af89-41b3-abcd-53d52cc3bba9.png)



## The expected behaviour:

ExcelJS works consistently regardless of context being run in.


## Possible solution (optional, but very helpful):

This is almost guaranteed to be the use of "instanceof" throughout the codebase, where doing "x instanceof Array" will return false inside a VM context. Similar to iFrames, the built-in class declarations are actually different in the new context. If this is the issue, then likely other things are broken inside a nodeVM as well.

https://github.com/nodejs/help/issues/2880
http://web.mit.edu/jwalden/www/isArray.html

These work...
- Array.isArray(x) 
- typeof (for base types)
- x.constructor.name === 'Array';
- Object.prototype.toString.call(obj) == '[object Array]'

These do not work...
- x instanceof Array
- x.constructor === Array

Array.isArray is preferred for checking arrays instead of instanceof specifically for this reason. Unfortunately checking other types requires checking constructor strings.

